title: For Sale/Trade:  2 old Browning 16 gauge shotguns
postcontent: 2 old Browning 16 gauge shotguns for sale or trade. Disclaimer: I am not an expert on this type of firearm, all information presented below is what I gathered from some basic online and blue book research. Of course some contradictory information was found, I am just going off of what made the most sense. I do not mind questions or information shared upon your own research/knowledge. I will be accepting offers, please make serious offers, these are fairly rare and valuable firearms. I will be posting on gunbroker individually soon, so if interested please make offers sooner rather than later. Top in pics: Browning Auto-5 16 gauge grade 2, serial number 91*** with an "H" stamped below it. I believe this dates it to the early 1930's. Barrel reads "BROWNING ARMS COMPANY OGDEN UTAH," "FULL 16 SPECIAL STEEL" and "MADE IN BELGIUM" with several proof marks. This was produced before the sweet 16 moniker came along. Receiver reads "FABRIQUE NATIONALE D'ARMES DE GUERRE HERSTAL BELGIQUE" and "BROWNINGS PATENT DEPOSE"Condition is good overall considering the age. Metal is in good condition with minor scratches here and there. Bore and chamber look good. Blueing overall is very good, one small spot on barrel where blueing has rubbed off. Wood is decent, with typical handling marks. The biggest flaw of the gun is there is a crack on the bottom side of forearm where it meets the receiver. Appears to be in factory condition to me. Bottom is pics: Browning Auto-5 "SWEET SIXTEEN", grade 2. Serial number puts it in the "X-Series" dating to 1953. The "X-series" are some of the more rare serial numbers of the sweet 16's, also has the vent rib running along barrel, which adds to the value. Takes 2 3/4" shells. Setup up more for shooting with a recoil pad and adjustable choke installed. The metal and blueing are in excellent shape, no flaws to speak of, even the screw heads look untouched. The wood does have handling marks but nothing I would consider damage. I can send additional pics if desired as armslist will only let me load a couple. I prefer cash but would consider a partial trade (see below). All laws apply of course, prefer to do transfers at East County Guns in Elma, but that can be negotiated depending on deal made.
